FIFA flipped the script on the rules. In past World Cups, overall goal difference was always the first tie-breaker. This year, head-to-head results are prioritized first for intra-group ties, matching the style used in the Euros and UEFA Champions League.
(a) Ranking Teams Within the Same Group
If two or more teams finish their three group matches tied on points (3 for a win, 1 for a draw, 0 for a loss), the following criteria are applied in exact order until the tie is broken:
1. Head-to-Head Points: Points earned only in the matches played between the tied teams.
2. Head-to-Head Goal Difference: Goal difference resulting only from matches played between the tied teams.
3. Head-to-Head Goals Scored: Total goals scored only in the matches between the tied teams.
4. Overall Goal Difference: Total goals scored minus total goals conceded across all three group matches.
5. Overall Goals Scored: Total number of goals scored across all three group matches.
6. Fair Play (Team Conduct) Score: The team with the cleanest disciplinary record wins. Teams start at 0 and lose points for cards accumulated across the three matches:
Yellow card: −1 point
Indirect red card (second yellow): −3 points
Direct red card: −4 points
Yellow card and direct red card: −5 points
7. FIFA World Ranking: The team's position in the official FIFA Men's World Ranking entry entering the tournament.
Corner Case: The Three-Way Tie
If three teams finish equal on points, a "mini-table" is created containing only those three teams (completely ignoring the fourth team's matches). Steps 1 through 3 are applied to this mini-league.
If this process successfully determines the rank of one team (e.g., Team A is clearly first) but leaves the other two (Team B and Team C) still completely tied, the comparison restarts from Step 1 exclusively between the two remaining tied teams before moving on to overall group metrics.
(b) Ranking the 8 Best 3rd-Place Teams
Once all 12 groups conclude, the 12 teams that finished in 3rd place are thrown into a single macro-table to determine which 8 squeeze into the knockout stage. Because these teams played in entirely different groups and never faced one another, head-to-head comparison is impossible.
Instead, they are ranked using group-wide statistics in this exact order:
1. Most Points: Total points accumulated in their respective group.
2. Highest Overall Goal Difference: Total goals scored minus goals conceded in their group.
3. Most Overall Goals Scored: Highest number of total goals scored in their group.
4. Fair Play Score: The fewest card penalty deductions across their three group matches.
5. FIFA World Ranking: The pre-tournament global ranking position.